<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is conduit fill?", answer: "Conduit fill is the percentage of a conduit's internal cross-sectional area that the insulated wires occupy. NEC Chapter 9 Table 1 limits fill to 53% for a single conductor, 31% for two, and 40% for three or more conductors. These limits allow for pulling friction, heat dissipation, and derating factors." },
  { question: "What conduit size do I need for three 12 AWG THWN-2 wires?", answer: "Each 12 AWG THWN-2 wire has a cross-section of 0.0133 sq in. Three wires total 0.0399 sq in, which at 40% fill needs a conduit with at least 0.0998 sq in interior area. 1/2\" EMT has 0.304 sq in — far more than needed. You can easily run three 12 AWG wires in 1/2\" EMT." },
  { question: "Why is the limit 40% for three or more wires?", answer: "With multiple wires, the irregular packing leaves unused space and increases pulling friction. 40% is the historical safe pulling limit established through manufacturer testing. Single-conductor fill can go as high as 53% because there's no interaction. Two-conductor is limited to 31% because of the 'jam ratio' — two wires of certain sizes can physically wedge against the conduit walls during pulling." },
  { question: "Does conduit fill include ground wires?", answer: "Yes — all current-carrying and grounding conductors count toward the fill. The equipment grounding conductor is usually sized smaller than the phase wires, so look up its actual area from NEC Chapter 9 Table 5 and add it to the total." },
  { question: "What is THWN-2 vs THHN?", answer: "THHN is a dry-location rated 90 °C conductor. THHN/THWN dual-rated conductors are rated for wet locations at 75 °C. THWN-2 is the newer designation for 90 °C wet rating. Most residential and commercial installations use THHN/THWN-2 dual-rated wire. Conduit fill dimensions are nearly identical across these types." }
]) %>

